How do you fix or replace a broken recall word?🤔 

First, make an intentional plan on creating a really good recall. The biggest part of having a great recall word is not using it in instances when it will be ignored. So how does that work? Unless you’re willing to bet me a thousand dollars that your dog’s going to come, don’t use your recall word. 

If you want to replace it, just start playing new games with your new word and keep that word sacred. It’s a special word, you want it to be valuable to your dog. You want it to be meaningful, so don’t let it lose its meaning or lose its value by using it when your dog’s less likely to respond to it properly, or by repeating it.

Don’t forget that activities your dog loves are high value reinforcers that should come through you, too. Every time you take your dog off to do barn hunt, or a sport, or a walk, or to the park: what is the thing before the thing? Most of the time the dog has learned the second or third time out, “I love this. I can’t wait to do it!” They might start squealing, pulling on leash, clawing to get closer to the activity they love. And then you reinforce that behavior by taking  off the leash. It’s “thing before the thing.” You’ve taught your dog to think, “In order to get what I want, I scream, I pull, I claw, and I get reinforced. I’m pulling on leash, I’m barking, you let me off, I go, I chase.”

It isn’t just about you training a certain way during a class for one hour a day and maybe practicing that certain way for ten minutes throughout the day.🚫That’s reinforcement based dog training done in isolation. But in order for reinforcement based dog training to be most effective, it’s got to be a way of life.✨It’s got to be the way you breathe. It’s got to be who you are. So you have to have an awareness of, ‘Where’s my dog getting the reinforcement now?’ And it’s not just about getting control over the dog. It’s about the safety of the dog. It’s about the dependability and the relationship that you share with that dog. You want a dog whose behaviors you can depend on. That it doesn’t matter if they see a rabbit, if they see a deer, if they see other dogs, you can just call them and they will come back. When you’ve gotten to that place, now you’re living in environmental neutrality. “Yes, I can get things, but the thing before the thing is I have to maybe get into Reinforcement Zone. I have to sit, down, stand, maybe turn around. Then I get released to the thing that I love most of all. To go and play bitey sports or to go and hunt birds.” Or you’re taking the value of the things a dog really, really loves and you are taking it on board for you so your dog understands it all goes through you. #DogsThat #SusanGarrett #ShapedByDog #ReinforcementBasedDogtraining #DogOwners #DogLovers

There’s a lot of people who teach dog agility and say, 📣“Week one, we’re going to put your dog in a tunnel. Week two, you’re going get on the dog walk.” If you want a dog who’s confident, who’s clear about what you want, please do not do that. Now, how does it get justified by people saying, “Oh, but Susan Garrett’s a world champion. All these people want to be world champions. We just want you to have fun.”

Oh, hell no.

What I want is, first and foremost, is fun for my dogs and fun for my students’ dogs.♥️✨ And that means safety first. And there’s still some people putting dogs on a collar and leash and dragging them over the equipment. No, never. Never. We want the dog to be empowered we want the dog to love what they’re doing. We want to make a connection. We want the dog to have this great relationship with you as they develop this great relationship with agility. And that doesn’t happen in eight weeks, my friend. But if you’re patient, as you build another layer, what’s also going to happen, you’re going to see, ‘WOW, my dog’s just so tuned into me now. WOW, my dog and I have this connection like we’ve never had before.” And that’s what being patient and putting in the layers of learning in dog agility will do for you and your dog.

So this happened…

Back in March I spoke to my friend @max.sprinz about getting a puppy from him in a year or two. Even though Kim has pretty much hijacked the ownership and training of 16 month old Belief now 😊but with This! still just turning 3 next month, I thought the timing would be perfect in a year or two. 

But then a month ago, I checked in on Max to see how he and his new litter of puppies were doing. At the exact moment he received my note, he was deciding upon who might be the future owners of the 10 puppies just born to his amazing dogs Remix X Style. Max said to me, “Do you believe in destiny? Because”, he went on to say, “I believe you were meant to have one of these puppies.” The puppies at the time were less than a week old. I told Max it was way too soon for me to consider another puppy but I’d think about it overnight and asked him to send me a video. 

That day, Max told @ramona_schuerken he believed that I would take a puppy, and he knew which puppy… and he was right. 
As soon as I looked at all the puppies,  I noticed how uniform the litter was, and how amazing all 10 puppies looked… but my heart was drawn to one immediately. 
I tried to ignore it, I mean, they weren’t even a week old. However, there was something very special about this puppy. As he got older, it became more and more obvious he was different. He had a calm energy about him, and I was head over heels in love. 
As fate would have it in Germany, where this litter was born, all of the puppies are registered the day they are born, and this puppy was given the name “Redefined Dedication” what a great name for this sweet soul. 
The litter is five weeks old tomorrow so he won’t be coming to Canada for a while yet, but I thought I’d share the news early. 

Welcome to the family “Prophet” I can’t wait to meet you in person. 

I also want to give a shout out to the amazing job of socialization, enrichment, environmental stimulation and love that Max and Ramona are giving to this litter of puppies. Clearly, they are breeders who love their dogs and their puppies and it’s truly inspiring to see.

🌈Over the years of raising puppies 🐶I’ve notice that some characteristics of any individual puppy will make them amazingly easy 🦄 to train some skills and those exact same characteristics will also make them more difficult to train other skills.

For example, Prophet has awe inspiring confidence, 💪💪💪he doesn’t need to be near me, he’s happy to play by himself. He is not one of those clingy,  in-your-face pups that always needs your attention and approval. I LOVE that about him. 

He is unflappable walking or training in new loud, distraction-filled environments. But here is a flip side to that confidence :). 🤔

I’ve observed that Prophet also appears to want to possess that which he values. Possibly coming from a litter of 10 puppies, where once you have a toy that is fun, you will soon have 9 littermates trying to get it from you! 🐾🐾

Or perhaps that has absolutely nothing to do with it 🤷‍♀️ being that Swagger, as a singleton, was exactly the same 🙈.

Right now my perfect 🇩🇪👑German Prince and I are working on his desire to bring a toy 🧸🦴that he loves TO ME :). 

Last week, if I was to lean or step towards him while he held a toy, he would run in the opposite direction 🧭🗺️with his treasure. 🤣😂 Yea, I enjoy the spark 🔥 of humour in a puppy. 

My advice to offer 🙏 to every puppy owner, is to be present to all that your puppy 🐶 is sharing with you. 

They are showing you THEIR priorities. Be present to this feedback. 
It could be 🚂🪀possessions, exploring, 🐽visiting, running🏃‍♂️scavenging etc. 

If your puppy’s priorities 🎉🏆do not mirror your priorities ☀️🧘‍♀️🛀then the difference should guide your future training sessions. 

From that information, you can make a training ✍️ 📓 plan.

For me with Prophet (as it was with Swagger) that means following the plan of my “Bring Me” mini course. I promise we will have a very impressive retrieve within a couple of weeks. 🤩⭐️☄️
